## 12. Hub taxa identification

Hub taxa can be defined in several ways. A transparent approach is to define hubs based on one or more centrality metrics.

Example using degree:

```r
hub_taxa_degree <- node_metrics %>%
  arrange(desc(degree)) %>%
  slice_head(n = 10)

hub_taxa_degree
```

Example using combined rank:

```r
hub_taxa_combined <- node_metrics %>%
  mutate(
    rank_degree = rank(-degree, ties.method = "average"),
    rank_eigenvector = rank(-eigenvector, ties.method = "average"),
    rank_betweenness = rank(-betweenness, ties.method = "average"),
    mean_rank = rowMeans(across(starts_with("rank_")), na.rm = TRUE)
  ) %>%
  arrange(mean_rank) %>%
  slice_head(n = 10)

hub_taxa_combined
```

Suggested wording:

```text
Hub taxa were defined as taxa ranking among the most central nodes according to degree and eigenvector centrality. These taxa were interpreted as highly connected members of the inferred association network, not necessarily as causal keystone taxa.
```

---

## 13. Exporting node and edge tables

Exporting networks as node and edge tables is useful for Cytoscape, Gephi, manual annotation, or reproducibility.

```r
edge_table <- as_data_frame(g, what = "edges")
node_table <- as_data_frame(g, what = "vertices")

write_csv(edge_table, "network_edges.csv")
write_csv(node_metrics, "network_nodes_with_metrics.csv")
```

If taxonomy is available, merge node metrics with taxonomy:

```r
tax_df <- as.data.frame(tax_table(ps)) %>%
  rownames_to_column("taxon")

node_metrics_tax <- node_metrics %>%
  left_join(tax_df, by = "taxon")

write_csv(node_metrics_tax, "network_nodes_with_taxonomy.csv")
```

