## 15. Recommended reporting checklist

When reporting microbiome network analysis, include:

1. Input data type: counts, estimated counts, relative abundances, or transformed abundances.
2. Taxonomic level: ASV, OTU, species, genus, family, etc.
3. Number of samples used for each network.
4. Number of taxa included after filtering.
5. Filtering criteria, reported elsewhere if not shown in the analysis script.
6. Network inference method.
7. Zero handling method.
8. Normalization or transformation method.
9. Sparsification or thresholding method.
10. Whether edges are signed or unsigned.
11. Number of nodes and edges.
12. Global network metrics.
13. Centrality metrics used to define hubs.
14. Whether formal network comparison was performed.
15. Whether the study design was paired or unpaired.

